<h3 class="story-teaser">By <a href="https://nightland.website/index.php/about/authors-and-artists/153-kate-coady">Kate Coady</a></h3>
<div class="story-intro"><a href="https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/the-science-of-the-night/257-the-fading-sun-part-1"><img class="story-thumb" src="https://nightland.website/images/thumbs/coady-red-sun-thumb.jpg" alt="A red sky over a cobblestone road that leads past alien plants toward a land of lava." /></a>The second part of an essay on the scientific and other inspirations of the cosmos in which Mr. Hodgson's speculative fiction takes place, by looking at <span class="book-title">The Night Land,</span> <span class="book-title">The House on the Borderland,</span> and H.G. Wells' <span class="book-title">The Time Machine.</span> In this section, I examine the first part of the far-future vision in <span class="book-title">The House on the Borderland.</span></div>
